Ivy Ross - Wikipedia






















 






Ivy Ross

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


					Jump to:					navigation, 					search





Ivy Ross


Ivy Ross (1955) is an American business executive and jewelry designer.[1] She was appointed Head of Google Glass at Google X[2] on May 19, 2014.[3] Ivy Ross’s metal work in jewelry design is in the permanent collections of 12 international museums, including the Smithsonian in Washington D.C.[4] One of few recognized fine artists to successfully cross over into the business world, Ross is also a keynote speaker[5] and a member of several boards, and has been hailed as a “creative visionary” by the art world.[6]



Contents


1 Background & Education
2 Career
3 Jewelry
4 Articles
5 Boards
6 Honors & Awards
7 Interviews
8 References



Background & Education[edit]
Ivy Ross was born in Yonkers, New York and grew up in Riverdale. She credits her father, an industrial engineer who worked for the Raymond Loewy studio that created the Studebaker Hawk automobile, for influencing her choice of careers.[7] Ross attended the High School of Art and Design in New York City, with a major in Fine Art and minor in Psychology. She later attended the Syracuse University School of Design and the Fashion Institute of Technology in New York City with a major in Jewelry Design. She went on to complete the Professional Management Development Program at Harvard Business School in 1994.
Career[edit]
Ivy Ross began her professional career as a designer. After college she launched a jewelry design business in 1978 called Small Wonders,.[8] Until the mid-‘80s, Ross worked as a designer for Avon Products Inc.[9] She oversaw product development for Swatch Watch and worked as an accessories designer for Liz Claiborne before moving on to direct design and product development for Outlook Eyewear (Bausch and Lomb), Coach, and Calvin Klein.
During Ross’s tenure at Mattel (1998 to 2004) as Senior Vice President of Worldwide Product Design & Brand Image for The Girls Division, she was charged with developing a new toy for the pre-teen girls segment. Ross conceived of an experiment in multi-disciplinary design dubbed “Project Platypus”,[10][11][12] which resulted in Mattel’s highly successful Ello Creation System.
After leaving Mattel, Ross joined the Gap Inc. as Executive VP of Product Design & Development for Old Navy from 2004 to 2007. While there, Ross created an in-house blog called "Culture Feed" with insight culled from the Internet and curated by trend-hunter Jody Turner.[13] She left to become Senior VP and Chief Creative Officer for the Disney Stores of America (owned by the Children’s Place),[14] a position she held for one year before returning to the Gap in 2008. As Executive Vice President of Marketing for the Gap Inc. Ross was responsible for the launch of the 1969 denim line of jeans. In July 2011, Ross joined Art.com[15] where she served as Chief Marketing Officer until her move to Google X in 2014.
Jewelry[edit]
Ivy Ross was one of the first jewelers to use titanium, tantalum, and niobium, metals that reveal a spectrum of colors when they are charged with electricity.[16] By age 26, Ross had some of her jewelry designs included in the permanent collections of 10 museums, including the Smithsonian,[17] the Victoria and Albert Museum[18] in London, the Museum of Arts and Design,[19] the Schmuckmuseum, in Pforzheim, Germany,[20] the Cooper-Hewitt, National Design Museum in New York City and the Montreal Visual Arts Center. Ross is a recognized American craft artist and has had her work exhibited globally.[21] In 1984 Ross and then-husband Robert Ebendorf won a Formica design competition through the exploration of a new product called ColorCore™.[22]
